{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476090"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13169"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.1,0.08,0.07,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5606"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24003"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1322"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8018"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy is brought to the GP by his parents due to an episode of acute gastroenteritis. During the physical examination, the doctor observes the presence of dark spots on the boy\u0027s abdomen (image). Upon closer inspection, a total of 13 such spots are identified on his trunk and limbs. The parents have been aware of these spots since infancy but have dismissed them as birthmarks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, the doctor notes the presence of multiple small lumps on the boy\u0027s skin (image), a condition that has primarily manifested within the past year. The patient also appears to be experiencing difficulties with his school performance. The boy\u0027s father exhibits similar skin lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tuberous sclerosis","McCune-Albright syndrome","Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome","Sturge-Weber syndrome","Neurofibromatosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurofibromatosis 1 (NF1)\u003C/strong\u003E, a relatively common autosomal dominant disorder affecting approximately 1 in 3000 individuals. It results from a gene mutation on chromosome 17, encoding neurofibromin. The typical order of appearance of clinical manifestations is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfancy: Presence of flat, uniformly hyperpigmented spots known as \u003Cem\u003ECaf\u00e9-au-lait \u003C/em\u003Emacules, which are present in nearly all patients. The presence of \u22656 \u003Cem\u003Ecaf\u00e9-au-lait\u003C/em\u003E macules strongly suggests NF1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChildhood: Axillary and/or inguinal freckling and Lisch nodules (iris hamartomas that do not affect vision)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELate childhood/early adolescence: Neurofibromas (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors composed of a mix of Schwann cells, fibroblasts, perineurial cells, and mast cells). Generally do not undergo malignant transformation, but can be disfiguring and may cause minimal or no clinical symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurologic deficits, such as gross motor delay, general incoordination, and school performance problems, affect approximately 60% of NF1 patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberous sclerosis (TS)\u003C/strong\u003E is another autosomal dominant genetic condition with neurocutaneous features. \u003Cem\u003ECaf\u00e9-au-lait \u003C/em\u003Emacules can also be present in TS, but this syndrome is further characterised by additional findings, including hypopigmented \u0027ash-leaf\u0027 spots, roughened patches of skin over the lumbar spine (Shagreen patches), and facial angiofibromas with a butterfly distribution over the nose. Neurological features such as developmental delay and intellectual impairment are also common, but epilepsy is a major manifestation in TS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMcCune-Albright syndrome (MAS) \u003C/strong\u003Eis classically defined by the clinical triad of fibrous dysplasia of bone (FD), \u003Cem\u003Ecaf\u00e9-au-lait\u003C/em\u003E macules (large segmental), and precocious puberty. FD can affect one or multiple skeletal sites, leading to a limp, pain, and, occasionally, pathologic fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Hippel-Lindau (VHL) \u003C/strong\u003Edisease is an inherited autosomal dominant syndrome characterised by a range of benign and malignant tumors. Renal cell carcinomas occur in approximately 2/3 of patients, and other potential tumors include cerebellar haemangiomas, retinal haemangiomas (resulting in vitreous haemorrhage), and phaeochromocytoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESturge-Weber syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, the third most common neurocutaneous syndrome following NF and TS, is characterised by often large capillary malformation involving the face (known as a \u0022port-wine stain\u0022), choroid, and leptomeninges. Seizures often represent the first neurological manifestation of Sturge-Weber syndrome, with infantile spasms occurring in roughly 90% of affected patients during their first year of life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neurofibromatosis is the most common neurocutaneous syndrome, with an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.","The typical order of appearance of clinical manifestations in NF1 is caf\u00e9-au-lait macules, axillary and/or inguinal freckling, Lisch nodules (iris hamartomas), and neurofibromas."],"references":["Gerber PA, Antal AS, Neumann NJ, Homey B, Matuschek C, Peiper M, et al. Neurofibromatosis. Eur J Med Res [Internet]. 2009 Dec [cited 2023 Sep 8];14(3):102-5. Available from: https://eurjmedres.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/2047-783X-14-3-102","Hirbe AC, Gutmann DH. Neurofibromatosis type 1: a multidisciplinary approach to care. Lancet Neurol [Internet]. 2014 Aug 1 [cited 2023 Sep 8];13(8):834-43. Available from: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laneur/article/piis1474-4422(14)70063-8/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24003"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20291"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20291"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SaiUi09UEilM1veynbCHqQEskYTJjO.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SaiUi09UEilM1veynbCHqQEskYTJjO.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":324}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24003"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-09-25T19:38:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T21:31:03+09:30